Been here ... lost track of how many times, but brenda's has never let me down. I've ordered the shrimp and grits multiple times and each time as perfect as the last. Other things I've ordered are the pork belly shrimp and grits, florentine eggs benedict, waffles, and of courseeeeee the beignets. My favorite is probably the crawfish beignet just because... well, I love crawfish. The servers are really polite and quick to attending to you, getting you fed and getting you out. Each time I've visited, I've never waited more than 15-20 mins for a table of about 2-4 people. But, I usually stay for about 45 mins to an hour or longer if with guests. Definitely worth trying if you haven't already!

Stopped by for a late lunch on a weekday, so there was no wait at all. Location is easy to get to, just a short walk away from Civic Center BART stop. Service was okay, nice and efficient. The tables & silverware were a little dirty, to the point where it was somewhat unappetizing, though I can still deal with it. Prices were decent. The dishes come in huge portions, so it's significantly cheaper if you share. We ordered the crawfish beignets and BFC (biscuit, fries, and fried chicken). Sooooo much food; I definitely recommend sharing. The crawfish beignets were pretty good, though a little heavy on the cayenne pepper so the outer shell tasted a bit powdery & dry. I would still re-order this dish though, as the filling is really tasty and it's a pretty unique dish. I enjoyed the BFC, though it didn't necessarily stand out over other southern fried chicken places I have tried. I would still recommend the BFC plate, but it's not something that I feel compelled to get every time I return. I will probably try more of their breakfast dishes next time and the shrimp & grits. I also had the sweet watermelon iced tea, which was okay, though I want to note it was very pulpy. They also serve alcohol here. Overall, I like the style of food at Brenda's and they do a pretty good job executing their menu. I would definitely return if I'm in the mood for a heavy brunch.

    Stopped by for a late lunch on a weekday, so there was no wait at all.  Location is easy to get to, just a short walk away from Civic Center BART stop.  

    Service was okay, nice and efficient.  The tables & silverware were a little dirty, to the point where it was somewhat unappetizing, though I can still deal with it.  Prices were decent.  The dishes come in huge portions, so it's significantly cheaper if you share.

    We ordered the crawfish beignets and BFC (biscuit, fries, and fried chicken).  Sooooo much food; I definitely recommend sharing.  The crawfish beignets were pretty good, though a little heavy on the cayenne pepper so the outer shell tasted a bit powdery & dry.  I would still re-order this dish though, as the filling is really tasty and it's a pretty unique dish.  I enjoyed the BFC, though it didn't necessarily stand out over other southern fried chicken places I have tried.  I would still recommend the BFC plate, but it's not something that I feel compelled to get every time I return.  I will probably try more of their breakfast dishes next time and the shrimp & grits.

    I also had the sweet watermelon iced tea, which was okay, though I want to note it was very pulpy.  They also serve alcohol here.

    Overall, I like the style of food at Brenda's and they do a pretty good job executing their menu.  I would definitely return if I'm in the mood for a heavy brunch.

    I will admit I have not had a lot of southern food in my life. Living in Vancouver good southern food is pretty sparse!  My friend and I came to San Francisco to visit three years ago and I was just trying to figure out some places for us to eat and we both thought the menu for this place sounded great, and of course quite different than anything we could get at home.

    My friend and I were so floored with how fantastic the food here was that this last May when we visited the city again we decided to go back and bring our other two friends.

    The restaurant itself is very contemporary looking and has a very warm atmosphere. Service was good. Food again was over the top amazing. Between the four of us, one of us got ribs, another got an oyster po boy and two of us got fried chicken-- all of which the dishes came with a variety of different things such as cornbread, coslaw, collard greens etc.  

    Once we all had a few bites of our own meals we all wanted to try each other's so we all ended up sharing each other's food and let me tell you the meals are huge! Even with two guys with us we had so much food left over.

    When my friend and I originally went we each ordered oyster po boy sandwiches that came with salad and fries and by the time we were stuffed we each had half a sandwich and sides left, we both could have shared one meal (yes we are both girls but we can both handle a reasonable amount of food). Sharing is a good suggestion if you aren't terribly starving.

    I love this place , I think it has already become a permanent staple restaurant for when we visit San Francisco now.
